08374nam a22009375i 9780226484716DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20081989ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226484716  a(DE-B1597)535631  a(OCoLC)1055419056  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHC79.S3 ǂb M43 1989eb 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a330 sa339.4/304aThe Measurement of Saving, Investment, and Wealth /ced. by Helen Stone Tice, Robert E. Lipsey. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©1989  a1 online resource (869 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research Studies in Income and Wealth ;v5200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrefatory Note -- tIntroduction -- t1 Present NIPA Saving Measures: Their Characteristics and Limitations -- t2 Measuring Household Saving: Recent Experience from the Flow-of-Funds Perspective -- t3 Flow-of-Funds and National Income and Product Account Savings Estimates in Latin America -- t4 Aggregate U. S. Private Saving: Conceptual Measures and Empirical Tests -- t5 The Accumulation of Human and Nonhuman Capital, 1948 -84 -- t6 Government Saving, Capital Formation, and Wealth in the United States, 1947-85 -- t7 The Theory and Measurement of the Nominal Output of Banks, Sectoral Rates of Savings, and Wealth in the National Accounts -- t8 World Payments Imbalances and U.S. Statistics -- t9 Year- Apar t Estimates of Household Net Worth from the Survey of Income and Program Participation -- t10 Survey Estimates of Wealth: An Assessment of Quality -- t11 Using Panel Data to Assess the Bias in Cross-sectional Inferences of Life-Cycle Changes in the Level and Composition of Household Wealth -- t12 The Wealth of the Aged and Nonaged, 1984 -- t13 Pension Wealth, Age-Wealth Profiles, and the Distribution of Net Worth -- t14 The Importance of Gifts and Inheritances among the Affluent -- t15 Long-Term Trends in U.S. Wealth Inequality: Methodological Issues and Results -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is probably no concept other than saving for which U.S. official agencies issue annual estimates that differ by more than a third, as they have done for net household saving, or for which reputable scholars claim that the correct measure is close to ten times the officially published one. Yet despite agreement among economists and policymakers on the importance of this measure, huge inconsistencies persist. Contributors to this volume investigate ways to improve aggregate and sectoral saving and investment estimates and analyze microdata from recent household wealth surveys. They provide analyses of National Income and Product Account (NIPA) and Flow-of-Funds measures and of saving and survey-based wealth estimates. Conceptual and methodological questions are discussed regarding long-term trends in the U.S. wealth inequality, age-wealth profiles, pensions and wealth distribution, and biases in inferences about life-cycle changes in saving and wealth. Some new assessments are offered for investment in human and nonhuman capital, the government contribution to national wealth, NIPA personal and corporate saving, and banking imputation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aSaving and investment. 0aWealth. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  asaving, investment, wealth, economics, economy, poverty, banking imputation, corporate, personal, nipa, government, capital, inequality, pensions, aging, flow of funds, latin america, estimates, national accounts, banks, finance, affluent, inheritance, gifts, intergenerational transfer, net worth, households, bias, accuracy, nonfiction.1 aAllen, Steven G., econtributor.4ct